Technology Documentary hosted by Scott McCord, published by Discovery Channel in 2011 - English narration


Information
------------------------------

Could YOU do it? Think about it: nearly one million people pass through Grand Central Terminal each day; 14,000 vessels navigate the Panama Canal every year; and 145 behind-the-scenes technicians keep audiences dazzled Ã‚â€“ and performers alive Ã‚â€“ during Cirque du SoleilÃ‚â€™s Ã‚â€œOÃ‚â€ on the Las Vegas strip. But who shoulders these pulse-pounding responsibilities? And, just how do they make their deadlines? NERVE CENTER offers an all-access pass revealing how some of the worldÃ‚â€™s most iconic Ã‚â€“ not to mention biggest and busiest Ã‚â€“ places keep ticking 24/7.


1)  Grand Central Terminal 
Grand Central Terminal moves 130,000 passengers a day over 400 miles of track and through 110 stations spread across New York City and upstate New York.

2)  Cirque du Soleils O 
Since its inaugural performance, Cirque Du Soleil's &quot;O&quot; has enthralled over 10 million spectators, during the course of 6000 shows.

3)  Panama Canal 
The Panama Canal is one of the largest canals in the world and shaves 8,000 miles off what would otherwise be a two-week voyage for the 14,000 vessels that pass through it annually; the most risky manouevre is when northbound ships meet southbound.

4)  Atlanta National Airport 
Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport manages 2,700 take-offs and landings and 250,000 passengers daily; it is most strained to capacity on Friday night at 19:24, when there are more planes in the air and on the ground then at any other time.

5)  DC Fire and EMS 
With over 150,000 calls each year, the District of Columbia Fire and EMS is one of the busiest all-hazardous agencies in the U.S.

6)  Port of Los Angeles 
The Port of Los Angeles is the biggest, busiest and most significant gateway in North America.

